SIMPLE: pawl
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pawl
<hw>Pawl</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[W. <ets>pawl</ets> a
pole, a stake. Cf. <er>Pole</er> a stake.]</ety> <fld>(Mach.)</fld>
<def>A pivoted tongue, or sliding bolt, on one part of a machine,
adapted to fall into notches, or interdental spaces, on another part, as
a ratchet wheel, in such a manner as to permit motion in one direction
and prevent it in the reverse, as in a windlass; a catch, click, or
detent. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>Ratchet Wheel</er>.</def>
<altsp>[Written also <asp>paul</asp>, or <asp>pall</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Pawl bitt</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a heavy
timber, set abaft the windlass, to receive the strain of the pawls.</cd>
-- <mcol><col><b>Pawl rim</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>Pawl
ring</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a stationary metallic ring
surrounding the base of a capstan, having notches for the pawls to catch
in.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pawl</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pawl
<hw>Pawl</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To stop with a pawl; to drop the
pawls off.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To pawl the capstan</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Capstan</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pawn</ent>⟦br⟧
